The constipation is due to opiates used during anesthesia. One side effect of opiates is constipation since they slow bowel motility. You can manage this post-operatively by using an osmotic stool softener like miralax, PEG, etc. These draw water in to your bowels. A stool softener can be used in combination if needed, like colace. You should ensure you're drinking a glass of water with the laxative and stay well hydrated. Adding insoluble fiber, like psyllium husk (metamucil) will help bulk the stool and make it easier to pass. You should not have to use a stimulant laxative.

&#x200B;

You will need to wait for the opiates to wear off and you will be back to normal. Your anesthetist may have other options like opiate-free anesthesia, etc. Those should be discussed with them and will vary based on the needs of your case.

I perscribed PrEP at my last job a bit.  I would mostly monitor for kidney issues.  Trouble swallowing would be quite unusual.  

&#x200B;

I suppose the twitching COULD be related to electrolyte abnormalities which COULD be related to kidney issues, but i'm going to be honest with you, it's a stretch.   You're OK to wait to talk to your ID doc.
